<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-05-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-05-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="622" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d622">
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg></opener>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Hunter</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Perry</persName></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#left">No. 98.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-05-16"><hi rend="italic">May</hi> 16, 1865.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> Your several despatches, from No 188, the
                            21st ultimo, to No. 191, of the 24th ultimo, together with your private
                            note, dated April 8, have been received. The thrilling account given in
                            your No. 190 of the effect produced in the Spanish capital by the news
                            of the fall of Richmond is highly interesting.</p>
                        <p rend="center">* * * * * * * * *</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant, </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>W. HUNTER, <hi rend="italic">Acting
                            Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Horatio</hi> J. <hi rend="smallcaps">Perry,</hi>
                                Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., Madrid.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>